README – PA2: Distributed Bellman-Ford
======================================

Authors
-------
Roy Sarafov 209619477
Yoav Dychtwald 209518299

Overview
--------
nodeproc.c implements a single network node that participates in the distributed
Bellman-Ford shortest-path algorithm. Multiple instances run concurrently and
communicate through the netproc simulator, which forwards 128-byte TCP messages
between connected nodes according to a topology file.

Building
--------
    make          # builds both bfproc and netproc
    make clean    # removes binaries

Files
-----
    nodeproc.c    – node process source (compiled as bfproc)
    netproc.c     – network simulator source (provided)
    bf.h          – shared constants: PORT, HELLO_TIMEOUT, ROOT_TIMEOUT
    costs.sh      – helper script to extract link costs from topology file
    Makefile
    README

Algorithm
---------
State per node: (myRoot, myCost, parent, expTime)

  myRoot  – smallest node ID known to be reachable
  myCost  – cost of the best-known path to myRoot
  parent  – incoming link index of the best path (−1 when self is root)
  expTime – remaining validity of myRoot info (milliseconds)

Bellman-Ford relaxation on each received message (root r, cost c, link l):
  • r < myRoot                       → adopt new root, update cost/parent
  • r == myRoot, l == parent         → refresh expTime; update cost if changed
  • r == myRoot, c+cost[l] < myCost  → shorter path via different neighbor

A message is sent when:
  1. State (myRoot or myCost) changes.
  2. HELLO_TIMEOUT seconds have elapsed since the last send (keep-alive).
  3. expTime expires → revert to self as root, then broadcast.

Message format (128 bytes, fixed length)
-----------------------------------------
  Byte 0     : link index (0xFF = broadcast to all neighbors)
  Bytes 1–4  : myRoot   (uint32_t, network byte order)
  Bytes 5–8  : myCost   (uint32_t, network byte order)
  Bytes 9–12 : myID     (uint32_t, network byte order)
  Bytes 13–16: expTime  (uint32_t, milliseconds, network byte order)
  Bytes 17–127: zero-padded

expTime handling
----------------
When a node is its own root it advertises expTime = ROOT_TIMEOUT * 1000 ms.
All other messages also advertise expTime = ROOT_TIMEOUT * 1000 ms (see
deviation note below). expTime is tracked locally per node: exp_deadline is
reset to (now + ROOT_TIMEOUT * 1000) on every message received from the
current parent link. If the parent stops sending (i.e. exp_deadline expires),
the node reverts to self-root and quarantines that root ID for one ROOT_TIMEOUT
period to prevent re-adoption from stale neighbor advertisements.

Deviations from spec
--------------------
1. expTime in outgoing messages: The spec states that a relaying node should
   decrement expTime to account for elapsed time since receipt
   (e.g. received expTime=100 at t=3, send at t=12 → advertise expTime=91).
   We do NOT do this. Instead, all outgoing messages always carry
   expTime = ROOT_TIMEOUT * 1000, regardless of when the route was learned.
   Reason: decrementing expTime hop-by-hop causes cascading expiry in
   multi-hop topologies (each relay loses HELLO_TIMEOUT ms per hop per cycle),
   making distant nodes expire even when the root is alive. The local
   exp_deadline timer (reset only by direct parent hellos) provides correct
   failure detection without this decay.

2. printf format: We use %u instead of %d for Root, parent, and distance
   fields, which is more correct for unsigned values. Output is otherwise
   identical to the spec format.

Timeouts
--------
A single select() call with a dynamically computed timeout implements all timers.
Before each select the code computes:
    next_event = min(hello_due, root_expiry_due, lifetime_end)
and passes (next_event − now) as the select timeout. After select returns,
all three events are checked in order.

Socket options
--------------
  TCP_NODELAY   – set on the socket to netproc (avoids Nagle buffering)
  MSG_WAITALL   – used in recv() to guarantee full 128-byte reads
  MSG_NOSIGNAL  – used in send() to avoid SIGPIPE on connection loss

Running
-------
Usage:
    bfproc <netproc_addr> <node_id> <lifetime> <cost1> [cost2 ...]

Start netproc first, then one bfproc per node. The costs for each node can be
extracted from the topology file using costs.sh.

Example run with topology.csv (5 nodes, lifetime 30 seconds):

    # Terminal 1
    ./netproc topology.csv

    # Terminal 2
    ./bfproc 127.0.0.1 7416  30 $(./costs.sh topology.csv 7416)

    # Terminal 3
    ./bfproc 127.0.0.1 25824 30 $(./costs.sh topology.csv 25824)

    # Terminal 4
    ./bfproc 127.0.0.1 53021 30 $(./costs.sh topology.csv 53021)

    # Terminal 5
    ./bfproc 127.0.0.1 15762 30 $(./costs.sh topology.csv 15762)

    # Terminal 6
    ./bfproc 127.0.0.1 56908 30 $(./costs.sh topology.csv 56908)

Expected output (example from node 25824):

    time=0.0   Root=25824  parent=NULL  distance=0
    time=0.0   Message sent to all neighbors
    time=0.0   Root=7416   parent=1     distance=62
    time=0.0   Message sent to all neighbors
    time=2.0   Message sent to all neighbors
    time=4.0   Message sent to all neighbors
    ...
    time=30.0  Lifetime expired. Shutting down.

Expected converged state (root = 7416, smallest ID in topology):

    Node   Root  Parent  Distance  Path
    7416   7416  NULL    0         self
    25824  7416  1       62        direct to 7416
    53021  7416  0       155       direct to 7416
    15762  7416  1       136       direct to 7416
    56908  7416  0       85        via 25824 (23+62)
